410→                           Erdős, Graham, Montgomery, Rothschild, Spencer, and Straus <a href="#cite-EGMRSS73-174" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('EGMRSS73','174'); return false;">[EGMRSS73]</a> proved that every Ramsey set is 'spherical': it lies on the surface of some sphere. Graham has conjectured that every spherical set is Ramsey. Leader, Russell, and Walters <a href="#cite-LRW12-174" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('LRW12','174'); return false;">[LRW12]</a> have alternatively conjectured that a set is Ramsey if and only if it is 'subtransitive': it can be embedded in some higher-dimensional set on which rotations act transitively.<br><br>Sets known to be Ramsey include vertices of $k$-dimensional rectangles <a href="#cite-EGMRSS73-174" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('EGMRSS73','174'); return false;">[EGMRSS73]</a>, non-degenerate simplices <a href="#cite-FrRo90-174" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('FrRo90','174'); return false;">[FrRo90]</a>, trapezoids <a href="#cite-Kr92-174" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Kr92','174'); return false;">[Kr92]</a>, and regular polygons/polyhedra <a href="#cite-Kr91-174" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Kr91','174'); return false;">[Kr91]</a>. 
